snippet.textDisplay: This is even harder now that we know it took a whole minute for the chopper to fall out of the sky and hit the ground. I was hoping they crashed into the side of the mountain and had no idea what was coming, quick, unexpected, and painless. Instead I'm left Imagining the panic, anxiety, and frustration he must have felt going down, knowing this was it, wanting to protect his daughter with every fiber of his being yet not being able to. What a horrific way to go. I'm crushed by this one. Something clicked for me when Shannon said he's "gone gone." Then it became real, it's just so damn final. So absolute. He's gone forever.. forever. Then I think about my own inevitable end and all the implications. Been a tough week

snippet.textDisplay: I work in the medical profession (critical care).  It's very difficult to have to tell an elderly woman there is nothing we can medically do for her husband of 49 years and watch her scream or see a baby placed on its dying mother's chest for one last time or see a son regretting not being able to say "I'm sorry" or "I forgive you" to his dying father.  My profession has taught me to appreciate life and the things that are most important in it: God, family, friends, health, forgiveness, love, etc. My profession reminds me every day that life is short.   It keeps me grounded and thankful for sure.  Take time to express to your loved ones and friends how much they mean to you.
